{"title_page": "Matt Revolter", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Matt Revolter\n| image        = Matt Revolter.jpg\n| caption      = Revolter in the self-portrait ''Impression''\n| birth_name   = Matthew Pappas\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age |1984|11|06|}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], [[California (state)|California]], United States\n| education   = [[Brooks Institute]]\n| nationality = Greek\n| residence = [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]], California\n| occupation   = Film producer, film director, [[cinematographer]], photographer\n| years_active = {{start date|2006}}&ndash;present\n| website      = {{url|www.mattrevolter.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Matt Revolter''' is an American film producer and photographer who is best known for producing music videos, short films, and fine art.\n\n==Biography==\n\n=== Early life ===\nRevolter was born and raised in [[Santa Barbara, California]]. He started as a [[graffiti artist]] and [[graphic designer]] before receiving a formal education in media production. He began his professional career working as an illustrator creating original works for corporate advertising, fashion companies, and musicians. During this time he also ran a successful marketing firm in Los Angeles, and has had success working as a commercial artist and marketer.<ref>{{cite web|author=Revolter Inc., LLC |url=http://revolterinc.com/history |title=It all started with\u2026 |url-status=dead |publisher=Revolter Inc., LLC |accessdate=February 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis work often deals with such themes as identity, empathy, and death. When he was ten years old his neighbor was attacked and killed by a [[great white shark]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-10/news/mn-7408_1_great-white-attacks |title=Shark Kills Skin Diver Off San Miguel Island : Death: Coast Guard officials believe a great white attacked James Robinson, who died of massive trauma. |url-status=live |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> Tragic life experiences have given him creative inspiration.\n\nRevolter has an extensive collection of vintage cameras, and has a preference to acquire items that often have connections to famous filmmakers or movies.<ref>{{cite web|author=Media Speak |url=http://articles.revolterinc.com/2010-08-02/article/rv_cameras |title=A Brief History of Cameras and Technology |url-status=dead |publisher=MediaSpeak |accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nRevolter graduated [[summa cum laude]] from [[Brooks Institute]], where he received a Master of Fine Arts in Photography, Bachelor of Fine Arts in Film, and a Certificate in [[Cinematography]].\n\n===Style===\nRevolter is known for creating empathetic and dark imagery set in high-concept settings. He claims to be \"format agnostic\" as he typically shoots with [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company]], [[Arri Alexa]], [[Hasselblad]], [[Phase One (company)|Phase One]], [[Leica Camera]], and [[Canon Inc.]] camera systems. He has incorporated principles derived from traditional cinema while shooting, which includes using film equipment and lighting techniques.<ref>{{cite web|author=RevInc |url=http://mattrevolter.com/about/ |title=Revolter's Camera Technique. |url-status=live |publisher=RevolterInc.com |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> Most of his scenes include real subjects in authentic locations, and he uses very little digital post-processing afterwards. Revolter's photographs are usually projected in large spaces, as opposed to being displayed in frames.\n\n== Career ==\n\n===Producer===\n\nIn 2014 Revolter produced a winning short film titled ''The Way We Were'', directed by Ayasylla Ghosn, for the [[Santa Barbara Film Festival]]'s 10-10-10 Student Filmmaking Competition.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3539790/?ref_=nm_flmg_prd_1\n |title=The Way We Were |url-status=live |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.keyt.com/news/students-participate-in-movie-making-competition/24395300 |title=Students Participate in Movie Making Competition |url-status=live |publisher=keyt.com |date=February 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> He also produced [[Schoolboy Q]]'s music video for \"Hoover Street\" that same year. In 2013 he produced the music video for [[Cali Swag District]]'s \"Shake Something\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Brooks Spotlight TV |url=https://vimeo.com/86166710 |title=Brooks Spotlight \u2013 \"Shake Somethin\" by Cali Swag District |url-status=live |via=Vimeo |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Photographer===\nIn 2015 Revolter installed a multimedia projection titled \"Bodies on the Wall\" on various buildings throughout California. The project was part of his graduating thesis and questioned how viewers analyzed, participated, and remembered their experiences regarding artwork in the digital age.<ref>{{cite web |author=VENUEMFA |url=http://mfa.brooks.edu/exhibition-announcement-second-nature-gallery-27/ |title=Exhibition Announcement {{!}} Second Nature {{!}} Gallery 27 |url-status=dead |publisher=mfa.brooks.edu |date=August 20, 2015 |accessdate=January 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222092004/http://mfa.brooks.edu/exhibition-announcement-second-nature-gallery-27/ |archive-date=February 22, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=INDEPENDENT|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2015/oct/06/good-bye-gallery-27/ |title=Good-bye Gallery 27 |url-status=live |work=Santa Barbara Independent |date=October 6, 2015 |accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Revolter's photography was installed on the Studio Wall at Brooks Institute. The images he displayed questioned the viewers' understanding of both the meaning, and the relationship between the photographs.<ref>{{cite web |author=HMartinez |url=http://mfa.brooks.edu/studio-wall-project-the-third-effect-matt-revolter/ |title=Studio Wall Project: \u2018The Third Effect' \u2013 Matt Revolter |url-status=dead |publisher=mfa.brooks.edu |date=March 29, 2014 |accessdate=July 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006132710/http://mfa.brooks.edu/studio-wall-project-the-third-effect-matt-revolter/ |archive-date=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography/exhibits==\nNotable work Revolter has produced include:\n\n===Short films===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role\n|-\n| 2014 || ''The Way We Were'' || Producer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3539790 |title=The Way We Were (Film)|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || ''The Visitation'' || Producer, production manager<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3231582 |title=The Visitation (Film)|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || ''Finale'' || Producer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2964352 |title=Finale (Film)|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || ''The BURB$'' || Executive producer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1USjoZ6-Zy0 |title=The BURB$ (Film)|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012 || ''CHUCK'D'' || Director, writer, editor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4903356 |title=CHUCK'D (Film)|accessdate=August 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Artist !! Song title !! Role\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Kembe X]] || \"As I Unfold\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nAZqDiw7W4U |title=As I Unfold (Music Video)|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> || Producer\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Schoolboy Q]] || \"Hoover Street\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ITM7AtxkaDU |title=Hoover Street (Music Video)|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> || Producer\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Cali Swag District]] || \"Pill Head\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SxdmMaeyDMA |title=Pill Head (Music Video)|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> || Producer\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Cali Swag District]] || \"Love Drug\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4TEEjTk59hw |title=Love Drug (Music Video)|accessdate=July 31, 2015}}</ref> || Producer\n|-\n| 2013 || [[Cali Swag District]] || \"Shake Somethin\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YrzAzO6xwHM |title=Shake Somethin (Music Video)|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> || Producer\n|-\n|}\n\n===Exhibitions===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Gallery !! City !! Type !! Type\n|-\n| 2016 || Deceptive Thoughts || Ethos Gallery || [[Santorini]], [[Greece]] || Solo || Installation (digital motion still projection)\n|-\n| 2015 || Bodies on the Wall<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mfa.brooks.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/secondnature_PR.pdf|title=Second Nature Press Release|accessdate=October 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006140246/http://mfa.brooks.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/secondnature_PR.pdf|archive-date=October 6, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> || Gallery 27 (Second Nature) || [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], [[California (state)|California]] || Group || Installation (digital motion still projection)\n|-\n| 2015 || Snap and Reframe<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visitventuraca.com/event/snap-reframe-brooks-institute-santa-barbara-international-film-festival-2015/ |title=Snap and Reframe|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> || [[Brooks Institute]] || [[Ventura, California|Ventura]], California || Group || Photography\n|-\n| 2014 || Convergence of Thought || Venice Art Wall || [[Venice Beach, California|Venice Beach]], California || Solo || Photographic paint installation\n|-\n| 2014 || Projected Dreams || Ethos Gallery (Projected Dreams) || Santorini, Greece || Solo || Installation (digital motion still projection)\n|-\n| 2014 || Third Effect<ref>{{cite web |author=HMartinez |url=http://mfa.brooks.edu/studio-wall-project-the-third-effect-matt-revolter/ |title=Studio Wall Project: \u2018The Third Effect' \u2013 Matt Revolter |url-status=dead |publisher=mfa.brooks.edu |date=March 29, 2014 |accessdate=July 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006132710/http://mfa.brooks.edu/studio-wall-project-the-third-effect-matt-revolter/ |archive-date=October 6, 2015 }}</ref> || [[Brooks Institute]] (Studio Wall Project) || [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], California || Group || Photography\n|-\n| 2012 || Intangible Assets || Stage C (Intangible Assets) || Ventura, California || Solo || Installation (digital motion still projection)\n|-\n| 2010 || Photosynthesis || The Estate || Los Angeles, California || Solo || Installation (digital motion still projection)\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|www.mattrevolter.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Revolter, Matt}}\n[[Category:Brooks Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Matt Revolter\n| image        = Matt Revolter.jpg\n| caption      = Revolter in the self-portrait ''Impression''\n| birth_name   = Matthew Pappas\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age |1984|11|06|}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], [[California (state)|California]], United States\n| education   = [[Brooks Institute]]\n| nationality = Greek\n| residence = [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]], California\n| occupation   = Film producer, film director, [[cinematographer]], photographer\n| years_active = {{start date|2006}}&ndash;present\n| website      = {{url|www.mattrevolter.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Matt Revolter''' is an American film producer and photographer who is best known for producing music videos, short films, and fine art.\n\n==Biography==\n\n=== Early life ===\nRevolter was born and raised in [[Santa Barbara, California]]. He started as a [[graffiti artist]] and [[graphic designer]] before receiving a formal education in media production. He began his professional career working as an illustrator creating original works for corporate advertising, fashion companies, and musicians. During this time he also ran a successful marketing firm in Los Angeles, and has had success working as a commercial artist and marketer.<ref>{{cite web|author=Revolter Inc., LLC |url=http://revolterinc.com/history |title=It all started with\u2026 |url-status=dead |publisher=Revolter Inc., LLC |accessdate=February 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis work often deals with such themes as identity, empathy, and death. When he was ten years old his neighbor was attacked and killed by a [[great white shark]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-12-10/news/mn-7408_1_great-white-attacks |title=Shark Kills Skin Diver Off San Miguel Island : Death: Coast Guard officials believe a great white attacked James Robinson, who died of massive trauma. |url-status=live |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> Tragic life experiences have given him creative inspiration.\n\nRevolter has an extensive collection of vintage cameras, and has a preference to acquire items that often have connections to famous filmmakers or movies.<ref>{{cite web|author=Media Speak |url=http://articles.revolterinc.com/2010-08-02/article/rv_cameras |title=A Brief History of Cameras and Technology |url-status=dead |publisher=MediaSpeak |accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nRevolter graduated [[summa cum laude]] from [[Brooks Institute]], where he received a Master of Fine Arts in Photography, Bachelor of Fine Arts in Film, and a Certificate in [[Cinematography]].\n\n===Style===\nRevolter is known for creating empathetic and dark imagery set in high-concept settings. He claims to be \"format agnostic\" as he typically shoots with [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company]], [[Arri Alexa]], [[Hasselblad]], [[Phase One (company)|Phase One]], [[Leica Camera]], and [[Canon Inc.]] camera systems. He has incorporated principles derived from traditional cinema while shooting, which includes using film equipment and lighting techniques.<ref>{{cite web|author=RevInc |url=http://mattrevolter.com/about/ |title=Revolter's Camera Technique. |url-status=live |publisher=RevolterInc.com |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> Most of his scenes include real subjects in authentic locations, and he uses very little digital post-processing afterwards. Revolter's photographs are usually projected in large spaces, as opposed to being displayed in frames.\n\n== Career ==\n\n===Producer===\n\nIn 2014 Revolter produced a winning short film titled ''The Way We Were'', directed by Ayasylla Ghosn, for the [[Santa Barbara Film Festival]]'s 10-10-10 Student Filmmaking Competition.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3539790/?ref_=nm_flmg_prd_1\n |title=The Way We Were |url-status=live |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=KEYT |url=http://www.keyt.com/news/students-participate-in-movie-making-competition/24395300 |title=Students Participate in Movie Making Competition |url-status=live |publisher=keyt.com |date=February 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> He also produced [[Schoolboy Q]]'s music video for \"Hoover Street\" that same year. In 2013 he produced the music video for [[Cali Swag District]]'s \"Shake Something\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Brooks Spotlight TV |url=https://vimeo.com/86166710 |title=Brooks Spotlight \u2013 \"Shake Somethin\" by Cali Swag District |url-status=live |via=Vimeo |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Photographer===\nIn 2015 Revolter installed a multimedia projection titled \"Bodies on the Wall\" on various buildings throughout California. The project was part of his graduating thesis and questioned how viewers analyzed, participated, and remembered their experiences regarding artwork in the digital age.<ref>{{cite web |author=VENUEMFA |url=http://mfa.